The '''National Athletic and Cycling Association''' ('''NACA''' or '''N.A. and C.A.'''), from 1990 the '''National Athletic and Cycling Association of Ireland''' ('''NACAI''' or '''NACA(I)''')<ref name="OCallaghan5"/> was a federation of sports clubs in [[Ireland|the island of Ireland]] practising [[Sport of athletics|athletics]] or [[bicycle racing]] or both. It existed from 1922 to 2000, though for most of the period it was not the sole governing body in Ireland for either sport. Its refusal to recognise [[partition of Ireland|the partition of Ireland]] got it expelled from the [[International Amateur Athletics Federation]] (IAAF) and the [[Union Cycliste Internationale]] (UCI). Clubs formerly in the NACAI are now affiliated to [[Athletics Ireland]] or [[Cycling Ireland]], each formed by the merger of the NACAI with rival bodies respectively affiliated to the IAAF and the UCI.

==Foundation==
The NACA was formed on 19 July 1922,<ref name="OCallaghan5">O'Callaghan (2012) p.5</ref> from a merger of the Irish Amateur Athletic Association or IAAA (including its subsidiary the [[cross country running|Cross Country]] Association of Ireland), the Irish Cycling Association (ICA) and the Athletics Council of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA).<ref name="athleticsireland"/><ref name="cain">{{Cite web |first=John |last=Sugden |author2=Scott Harvie |year=1995 |url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/csc/reports/sugdenharvie/sugdenharvie95-1.htm |title=Sport and Community Relations in Northern Ireland}}</ref> The GAA was [[Irish nationalist]] and mainly rural, while the IAAA and ICA members were mainly [[Irish unionist|unionists]], universities, and the urban middle class. The IAAA was linked to the [[Amateur Athletic Association of England]] (AAA).

The unionist-dominated [[Northern Ireland]] and the nationalist [[Irish Free State]] had recently been separated politically, and the GAA was prepared to surrender its authority to ensure national unity in athletics and cycling and avoid a division which would reinforce the reality of partition. The GAA after 1923 thus restricted itself to [[Gaelic games]], ceding athletics and cycling to NACA, with which it remained on friendly terms.  [[John J. Keane (Olympics)|John J. Keane]], previously Chairman of the GAA Athletic Council, became first NACA President.<ref>O'Callaghan (2012) pp.1,4</ref> Whereas the GAA had [[Rule 21|a ban on members of the RUC and British Army]], the NACA narrowly voted not to introduce such a measure.<ref>Coyle 2003, p.192</ref>

The NACA affiliated to the IAAF on 11 January 1924,<ref name="OCallaghan5"/> and sent teams to the Olympics of [[Ireland at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924]], [[Ireland at the 1928 Summer Olympics|1928]], and [[Ireland at the 1932 Summer Olympics|1932]].<ref name="athleticsireland"/> It also sent [[Ireland at the Commonwealth Games#1930|five athletes]] to the [[1930 British Empire Games]] in Canada. In each case, the team was claimed to represent "Ireland" rather than the Irish Free State.

In 1937, the National Cycling Association (NCA) was formed as a NACA subsidiary for cycling clubs, and affiliated to the UCI. The [[Rás Tailteann]] was its headline event, an 8-day stage race whose name reflected the [[Tailteann Games (ancient)|Tailteann Games]].

==Splits and isolation==
Already by 1925 there was a split, with the Northern Ireland Amateur Athletic, Cycling and Cross Country Association (NIAAA) formed over a dispute concerning an Easter Monday sports meeting in Belfast, which as well as athletics featured [[greyhound racing]] and associated betting, which had been allowed by the IAAA but not by NACA.<ref name="reynolds">{{cite journal |url=http://www.historyireland.com/20th-century-contemporary-history/a-first-class-splitpolitical-conflict-in-irish-athletics-1924-40/ |title='A first-class split':political conflict in Irish athletics, 1924–40 |journal=History Ireland |volume=20 |issue=4 |date=July–August 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2013 |first=Pearse |last=Reynolds |location=Dublin }}</ref> Since the meeting was to raise funds for [[Belfast Celtic F.C.]], with an [[Irish nationalist]] fanbase, the NACA alienated nationalists as well as unionists in Belfast.<ref name="reynolds" /> The NIAAA affiliated to the English AAA in 1930, with its unionist president [[Thomas Moles]] encouraging links within the UK,<ref name="athleticsireland"/><ref name="reynolds" /> and [[Dawson Bates]], the [[Minister of Home Affairs (Northern Ireland)|NI Home Affairs minister]], lobbying the AAA.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hunt |first1=Tom |title=The National Athletic Association of Ireland and Irish Athletics, 1922–1937: steps on the road to athletic isolation |journal=Sport in Society |date=17 July 2015 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=130–146 |doi=10.1080/17430437.2015.1038918}}; reprinted as  {{cite book |editor-last1=Hassan |editor-first1=David |editor-last2=McElligott |editor-first2=Richard |title=A Social and Cultural History of Sport in Ireland |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781317326472 |url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=xnRUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT310 |accessdate=30 July 2018 |language=en |chapter=Chapter 10}}</ref>

In 1931, [[Eoin O'Duffy]] was president of the NACA, and raised at the IAAF the dispute with the British AAA over jurisdiction over Northern Ireland. The IAAF deferred a decision till its conference at the [[1932 Summer Olympics|1932 Olympics]].<ref name="reynolds" /> In the meantime O'Duffy tried to resolve the matter by proposing an Irish Amateur Athletic Union (IAAU) in negotiations between NACA and the NIAAA, to have an agreed flag containing the arms of the four provinces on a background of [[St Patrick's Blue]].<ref name="reynolds" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Sports flag question|date=29 February 1932|work=The Irish Times|page=7}}</ref> However, the proposal foundered when an NACA general meeting insisted that the flag used at international events be the [[Irish tricolour]] rather than the IAAU flag.<ref name="reynolds" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Irish athletics and a flag|date=4 April 1932|work=The Irish Times|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Northern athletics and the flag|date=30 April 1932|work=The Irish Times|page=9}}</ref> The IAAF decided in 1932 not to intervene in the Northern jurisdcition dispute.<ref name="reynolds" />

In 1934, the IAAF amended its constitution to require member associations to be delimited by international political boundaries.<ref name="athleticsireland"/><ref name="reynolds" /> After a year's delay, the NACA council voted 24 to 27 to reject the IAAF decision and was suspended the following month.<ref name="athleticsireland"/><ref name="reynolds" /> There was no Irish team at the [[1936 Summer Olympics|1936 Olympics]], other Irish sports boycotting in solidarity with the NACA exclusion.<ref name="reynolds" /> In 1937, some clubs in the Irish Free State left NACA and formed an Irish Amateur Athletic Union (IAAU, the same name as the abortive 1932 proposal) whose remit excluded Northern Ireland.<ref name="athleticsireland"/> The IAAU applied to join the IAAF, but due to [[Names of the Irish state#Name dispute with the UK|British objections to the name "Ireland"]] was required to rename itself the Amateur Athletic Union of [[Éire]] (AAUE).<ref name="reynolds" /> AAUE affiliation in 1938 meant the NACA was definitively expelled from the IAAF.<ref name="athleticsireland"/><ref>O'Callaghan (2012) pp.4–5</ref> Most Irish athletics clubs remained in NACA, and it was NACA that was affiliated to the [[Irish Olympic Council]], though it was AAUE athletes who competed at the Olympics.<ref name="sullivan">{{cite journal |last=O'Sullivan |first=Patrick T.  |date=Spring 1998 |title=Ireland & the Olympic Games |journal=History Ireland |location=Dublin |volume=6 |issue=1 |url=http://www.historyireland.com/volumes/volume6/issue1/features/?id=180 }}</ref> [[Ronnie Delany]]'s gold medal in the [[Athletics at the 1956 Summer Olympics – Men's 1500 metres|1956 1500 m]] was not mentioned at the next NACA executive meeting.<ref>Coyle 2003, p.195</ref>

The UCI emulated the IAAF in 1947 by requiring the NCA to disclaim Northern Ireland, expelling it when it refused. In 1949, several clubs broke away from the NCA to form Cumann Rothaíochta na hÉireann (CRE), which would restrict its area of jurisdiction to the [[Republic of Ireland]]. The CRE was recognised by the UCI, as was the Northern Ireland Cycling Federation (NICF), formed the same year and linked to the [[British Cycling|British Cycling Federation]].<ref name="cain"/> The CRE and NICF co-operated and organised the [[Tour of Ireland]], which attracted fewer Irish cyclists than the Rás Tailteann but more from abroad. A joint CRE-NICF Ireland team competed in international events, from which the NCA was excluded. Rogue NCA teams joined the [[1955 UCI Road World Championships|1955 amateur world road race championship]] and the [[Cycling at the 1972 Summer Olympics – Men's individual road race|1972 Olympics road race]] in protest at their exclusion.<ref name="cain"/>

The NACA retained some international links, through the [[International Labour Sports Federation]] (CSIT).<ref>Coyle 2003, pp.203–4</ref>

==Dissolution==
In 1979, the NCA joined the NICF and the Irish Cycling Federation (ICF; the renamed CRE) in the Irish Cycling Tripartite Committee (ICTC).<ref name="cain"/> In 1987 all three merged into the Federation of Irish Cyclists (FIC),<ref name="cain"/> later renamed [[Cycling Ireland]].

After many failed attempts at unification, Bord Luthchleas na hÉireann (BLÉ) was formed in 1967 by the merger of the AAUE and most clubs of the NACA.<ref name="athleticsireland"/> However, some NACA clubs refused to join BLÉ, though in 1987 the rump NACA reached agreement with BLÉ allowing joint international representation.<ref name="athleticsireland"/> In 2000, both bodies were dissolved into the Athletics Association of Ireland, which forms [[Athletics Ireland]] together with the NIAAA.<ref name="athleticsireland">{{cite web | url=http://www.athleticsireland.ie/content/?page_id=5990 | title=History | publisher=Athletics Ireland | accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>

