{{Orphan|date=March 2015}}
The '''National Precursor Log Exchange''' (NPLEx) is a real-time electronic logging system which tracks sales of the [[methamphetamine]] [[Precursor (chemistry)|precursors]] [[ephedrine]] and [[pseudoephedrine]] in the [[United States]]. The program is operated by the [[National Association of Drug Diversion Investigators]] (NADDI), funded by manufacturers of pseudoephedrine medicine, and technology provided through contract by [[Apriss Inc]].<ref name="nplexfaq">{{Cite web | title = NPLEx - National Precursor Log Exchange | url = http://nplexservice.com/faq.html | publisher = Apriss Inc. | accessdate = 14 January 2014 }}</ref> As of January 2014, 29 states have passed NPLEx-related legislation,<ref name="shelby2014_a">{{Cite web | title = Anti-meth efforts have little impact: State report | url = http://www.t-g.com/story/2040605.html | publisher = Shelbyville Times-Gazette | date = 12 January 2014 | accessdate = 14 January 2014 }}</ref> and it is implemented in most other states on a voluntary basis by national retail chains.
Whenever an individual purchases a precursor medicine from a participating retailer, identifying information is gathered at the point of sale and submitted to NPLEx. The system cross-references the sale to other purchases made by that individual to determine whether that person has purchased in excess of daily and monthly legal quantities. The sale may optionally be blocked, and the record is made available to law enforcement over the Internet.<ref name="nplexfaq" />
== Criticism == Multiple law enforcement agencies have reported that the system is not effective at stopping meth production.<ref name="shelby2014_b">{{Cite web | title = Anti-meth efforts have little impact: State report (01/12/14) | url = http://www.t-g.com/story/2040605.html | publisher = Shelbyville Times-Gazette | date = 12 January 2014 | accessdate = 14 January 2014}}</ref><ref name="watchdog30mar2014">{{Cite web | title = Cops say state database 'does nothing to stop meth labs' | url = http://watchdog.org/34952/vashn-law-enforcement-calls-nplex-an-incremental-solution-to-meth-problem/ | publisher = Virginia Statehouse News | date = 30 March 2012 | accessdate = 14 January 2014}}</ref><ref name="tncomp2014">{{Cite web | title = 2014 Follow-up Report: Methamphetamine Production in Tennessee | url = http://www.comptroller.tn.gov/Repository/RE/Meth%202014.pdf | date = January 2014 | accessdate = 14 January 2014 }}</ref><ref name="gwgaz2013">{{Cite web | title = Chief deputy: Meth-making tracker system not working | url = http://www.wvgazette.com/News/201306260134 | publisher = The Charlestone Gazette | date = 26 June 2013 | accessdate = 14 January 2014 }}</ref> The system is vulnerable to "smurfing", a practice where multiple individuals work together by each buying a legal quantity of precursors and pooling them.<ref name="watchdog30mar2014" /> The blurring of the responsibilities of government and private business has been called into question,<ref name="azrepub2012">{{Cite web | title = Computers to help limit sale of meth ingredients | url = http://nplexservice.com/documents/ArizonaNPLEx.pdf | publisher = The Arizona Republic | date = 19 June 2012 | accessdate = 14 January 2014}}</ref> as well as privacy concerns arising from the accuracy and retention of records.<ref name="watchdog22mar2012">{{Cite web | title = New VA law helps criminalize 'sniffles' and invades privacy | url = http://watchdog.org/34951/vashn-new-va-law-helps-criminalize-sniffles-invade-privacy/ | publisher = Virginia Statehouse News | date = 22 March 2012 | accessdate = 14 January 2014 }}</ref>
