{{For|the film adaptations|Op Hoop van Zegen (films)}}
{{italic title}}
{{citation style|date=July 2011}}
[[File:Op Hoop Van Zegen 20.png|thumb|Set image with [[Kitty Courbois]], {{ill|Liane Saalborn|nl}}, {{ill|Hetty Verhoogt|nl}}, {{ill|Mimi Boesnach|nl}} and [[Riek Schagen]].]]
'''''Op Hoop van Zegen''''' (Dutch for "Hoping for the best"), is a 1900 Dutch play, taking place in a fishing village, with the conflict between the [[fisherman|fishermen]] and their employer ending in [[tragedy]] with the unsound boat setting out to sea and sinking with all hands and the owner pocketing the insurance money. It is still staged, and remains the most popular play by Dutch dramatist [[Herman Heijermans]]. The socialist Heijermans is considered to have meant the play as a criticism of the entire [[capitalist]] system, though some present-day productions downplay this radical approach.

There are four films based on the play. The most recent was made in 1986, featuring [[Danny de Munk]] as ''Barend''.

