'''Peppermint extract''' is an [[herbal extract]] of [[peppermint]] (''Mentha x piperita'') made from the [[essential oils]] of peppermint leaves. It is commonly used in [[cooking]], as a [[dietary supplement]], as an herbal or [[alternative medicine]], and as a pest repellent. The liquid is obtained by [[Liquid-liquid extraction|extracting]] the oils from dried or fresh leaves and the flowering tops of the plant using [[alcohol]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}} and is commonly sold in 1 oz. or 4 oz. bottles.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}
==Uses in cooking== {{unreferenced section|date=February 2015}} Peppermint extract can be used to add a peppermint flavor to [[baked goods]], [[desserts]], and [[candy]], particularly [[candy canes]], [[mint (candy)|mints]], and peppermint patties. Extracts for cooking may be labeled as pure, natural, imitation, or artificial. While pure and natural extracts contain peppermint oil specifically, imitation and artificial extracts generally use a mix of ingredients to achieve a flavor resembling peppermint.
Peppermint extract can be substituted in [[recipes]] with peppermint oil (a stronger ingredient primarily used in candy-making), [[crème de menthe]], or [[schnapps|peppermint schnapps]]. If the food is not heated, the [[alcohol|alcoholic properties]] of [[liqueurs]] may remain present in the finished product.
Peppermint extract may also be added to hot water to create [[peppermint tea]].
== Medicinal uses == Medicinal uses of peppermint extract are well-documented, however the efficacy of most applications is only beginning to be confirmed in clinical trials. For example, Peppermint extract is commonly used to soothe symptoms of the [[common cold]] and the [[flu]], and as a [[digestion|digestive]] aid to relieve [[bloating]] and [[flatulence]]. It may be used to aid in the relief of pain from [[menstrual cramp]]s<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.hermed.2016.05.001 |title=The effect of peppermint (Mentha piperita) capsules on the severity of primary dysmenorrhea |journal=Journal of Herbal Medicine |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=137–141 |year=2016 |last1=Heshmati |first1=Akram |last2=Dolatian |first2=Mahrokh |last3=Mojab |first3=Faraze |last4=Shakeri |first4=Nozhat |last5=Nikkhah |first5=Somayeh |last6=Mahmoodi |first6=Zohreh }}</ref> and [[tension headaches]],{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} and because of its cooling properties, it may relieve itching when applied [[topical]]ly.{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} Additionally, peppermint oil may be an effective remedy for [[Irritable Bowel Syndrome]] (IBS) with constipation,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.a2313 |pmid=19008265 |pmc=2583392 |title=Effect of fibre, antispasmodics, and peppermint oil in the treatment of irritable bowel syndrome: Systematic review and meta-analysis |journal=BMJ |volume=337 |pages=a2313 |year=2008 |last1=Ford |first1=A. C |last2=Talley |first2=N. J |last3=Spiegel |first3=B. M R |last4=Foxx-Orenstein |first4=A. E |last5=Schiller |first5=L |last6=Quigley |first6=E. M M |last7=Moayyedi |first7=P }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S1590-8658(06)80548-7 |title=Peppermint oil (Mintoil®) in the treatment of irritable bowel syndrome. A prospective double blind placebo controlled randomized trial |journal=Digestive and Liver Disease |volume=38 |pages=S202 |year=2006 |last1=Cappello |first1=G |last2=Coraggio |first2=D |last3=De Berardinis |first3=G |last4=Spezzaferro |first4=M |last5=Grossi |first5=L |last6=Marzio |first6=L }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.phymed.2004.10.005 |title=Peppermint oil in irritable bowel syndrome |journal=Phytomedicine |volume=12 |issue=8 |pages=601–606 |year=2005 |last1=Grigoleit |first1=H.-G |last2=Grigoleit |first2=P }}</ref> particularly in capsule form, which bypasses the stomach in order to act in the [[small intestine]].{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}.It is also used as a natural remedy for [[toothache]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toothpainremedies.net/peppermint-oil-toothache/ |title=Peppermint oil as toothache remedy }}{{rs|date=August 2018}}{{dead link|date=August 2018}}</ref> Moreover, peppermint extract is believed to have [[Antiviral drug|antiviral]] and medicinal properties which may help in the treatment of [[herpes]] and the disintegration of [[gallstones]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}}
==Use as a pest repellent== Peppermint oil is commonly used to repel ants, flying insects, and rodents,.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gardenguides.com/81346-use-peppermint-oil-pest-control.html|website=GardenGuides.com|title=How to Use Peppermint Oil for Pest Control}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204563304574318231044370704|title=Death by Mint Oil: Natural Pesticides | author=Bounds, Gwendolyn|date=July 30, 2009 | work=Wall Street Journal}}</ref>
==Use as a physical performance enhancer== Peppermint oil is used in endurance sports to improve mental and physical stamina.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=25050303 |pmc=4103722 |year=2014 |last1=Meamarbashi |first1=A |title=Instant effects of peppermint essential oil on the physiological parameters and exercise performance |journal=Avicenna Journal of Phytomedicine |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=72–8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/1550-2783-10-15 |pmid=23517650 |pmc=3607906 |title=The effects of peppermint on exercise performance |journal=Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=15 |year=2013 |last1=Meamarbashi |first1=Abbas |last2=Rajabi |first2=Ali }}</ref>
